01:54.324 --> 01:56.368
After reading that first
National Lampoon,

01:56.534 --> 01:59.787
I went, "Wow, that's what
I've been trying to say."

02:02.582 --> 02:04.709
National Lampoon
just meant a lot to me as a kid

02:04.876 --> 02:06.586
because it was
what I wanted to do.

02:06.753 --> 02:09.380
It woke me up to the idea
that this was a job.

02:09.547 --> 02:12.383
Fat, drunk and stupid is
no way to go through life, son.

02:12.967 --> 02:15.470
Judd Apatow: And then you get
all these generations afterwards

02:15.804 --> 02:19.140
of people like me who were
just trying to be those guys.

02:21.017 --> 02:23.812
It was sharp, crystal clear,
and above all funny.

02:25.104 --> 02:27.065
It just blew
the whole shit house up.

02:27.273 --> 02:29.609
[music] (music continues) [music]

02:33.780 --> 02:39.285
The National Lampoon was
defining part of the zeitgeist.

02:41.120 --> 02:45.416
Here was this totally
outrageous voice

02:45.583 --> 02:49.921
that was screaming,
"Here I come."

02:50.088 --> 02:53.299
[music] (music continues) [music]

02:55.510 --> 02:58.555
Breasts... I would try
to seek out the magazine

02:58.721 --> 03:01.266
on the off chance that
there would be some breasts.

03:01.432 --> 03:05.353
[music] (music continues) [music]

03:05.520 --> 03:08.898
Kevin Bacon: The humor was
a little bit above my pay grade.

03:09.274 --> 03:11.150
(chuckling)

03:12.110 --> 03:14.779
Meatball: The Lampoons
are very intellectual.

03:15.196 --> 03:16.906
Tennessee Williams
and Arthur Miller

03:17.073 --> 03:19.367
could have been part
of National Lampoon.

03:19.534 --> 03:22.579
We were taking on the idiocy

03:23.288 --> 03:25.164
of our own generation.

03:25.331 --> 03:27.500
You know, overthrowing the ageist,
racist, sexist,

03:27.667 --> 03:30.253
corporate pig monster
is a full-time job.

03:32.005 --> 03:34.090
They always had
the best parties,

03:34.340 --> 03:37.343
the best drugs,
the smartest people.

03:41.848 --> 03:43.016
We could sell out more,

03:43.892 --> 03:46.853
and the moment
we do sell out totally,

03:48.229 --> 03:49.355
we'll be dead.

03:49.522 --> 03:53.443
[music] (music continues) [music]

04:06.956 --> 04:08.750
There's a time
in everyone's life,

04:09.542 --> 04:12.962
and it's really
between 17 and 22,

04:13.129 --> 04:15.590
when you talk to people
in their middle age,

04:15.757 --> 04:17.716
they always talk
about their high school

04:17.884 --> 04:20.303
or their college experience
as the, quote unquote,

04:20.470 --> 04:22.055
"Best years of their lives."

04:22.305 --> 04:23.806
And I'm thinking, "Well, why?"

04:23.973 --> 04:28.603
And ultimately it's because,
when you're 17, 18,

04:28.770 --> 04:32.774
you were expected to function
as an adult, but you're a baby.

04:33.566 --> 04:35.086
Have you ever gone
to a college campus?

04:35.109 --> 04:36.194
Those kids are babies.

04:36.361 --> 04:37.904
But they're adults,

04:38.071 --> 04:41.491
so there's this wonderful
freedom, sense of adventure.

04:41.866 --> 04:45.119
"We can do anything we want!
We're college students!"

04:45.453 --> 04:47.413
And that's really
how the whole thing started.

04:47.580 --> 04:50.959
[music] (piano plays) [music]

04:51.125 --> 04:54.337
[music] Fight fiercely, Harvard
fight, fight, fight [music]

04:54.504 --> 04:57.215
[music] Impress them
with our prowess do [music]

04:57.382 --> 04:58.466
Meatloaf:
What was it originally,

04:58.633 --> 04:59.968
the Harvard Lampoon, right?

05:00.134 --> 05:01.636
Well, anybody that
mentioned Harvard,

05:01.803 --> 05:03.805
I just went, "Fuck you."

05:04.180 --> 05:06.808
The Harvard Lampoon
was one of those famous things

05:06.975 --> 05:08.393
that nobody has
ever seen a copy of.

05:08.559 --> 05:10.079
[music] Fight, fight, fight... [music]

05:10.103 --> 05:11.229
Mike Reiss:
The Harvard Lampoon is

05:11.396 --> 05:13.189
America's oldest humor magazine

05:13.356 --> 05:16.442
started at Harvard in 1876.

05:16.609 --> 05:18.194
Man: John Updike was an editor,

05:18.361 --> 05:20.363
and George Plimpton was
an editor.

05:20.863 --> 05:22.490
Well, that's about it, you know?

05:22.949 --> 05:25.827
Two famous writers in 125 years.

05:26.369 --> 05:29.247
And we also had Fred Gwynne, the
guy who played Herman Munster.

05:29.539 --> 05:31.541
It goes
off the table after that.

05:31.708 --> 05:35.045
[music] Fight, fight, fight [music]

05:35.503 --> 05:38.214
Harvard Lampoon was just
this extracurricular activity

05:38.381 --> 05:40.049
and was something
you did before you went

05:40.216 --> 05:43.136
into the family law firm
or became a banker.

05:47.390 --> 05:50.852
Doug Kenney and Henry Beard were
in the class after I left Harvard.

05:51.060 --> 05:52.979
They were both incredibly brilliant,

05:53.146 --> 05:56.941
and incredibly funny
and incredibly good friends,

05:57.108 --> 05:58.735
but they weren't the same at all.

06:04.782 --> 06:07.243
Doug Kenney was really the heart
and soul of the Lampoon.

06:07.410 --> 06:10.663
Doug was the, sort of, the complete
social opposite of Henry.

06:10.830 --> 06:13.124
For one thing, he did not come
from an upper-crust family.

06:13.291 --> 06:15.960
Doug's father was the tennis pro

06:16.127 --> 06:19.255
at a golf club
in Chagrin Falls, Ohio.

06:19.797 --> 06:21.674
Have you ever seen Caddyshack?
That's Doug.

06:22.425 --> 06:23.885
- You take drugs, Danny?
- Every day.

06:24.052 --> 06:25.178
Good.

06:25.553 --> 06:27.013
Tony Hendra:
The very first time I met Doug,

06:27.180 --> 06:29.891
he was talking like
William Makepeace Thackeray.

06:30.058 --> 06:33.395
I mean, he was actually
improvising his prose, right?

06:33.561 --> 06:35.354
And it was Thackeray,
it wasn't Dickens.

06:35.521 --> 06:38.691
And about 30,
45 seconds after that,

06:38.858 --> 06:41.819
he was demonstrating that he could
put his entire fist in his mouth.

06:42.445 --> 06:44.072
So this was Doug, you know?

06:44.447 --> 06:46.658
Sean Kelly: Doug was a performer.

06:46.949 --> 06:48.409
Doug wanted to be a star.

06:48.576 --> 06:50.411
And he was a smart, funny,

06:50.578 --> 06:52.497
complicated person
who could write.

06:52.663 --> 06:54.415
Now that's, uh, that's rare.

07:07.887 --> 07:09.847
Bruce McCall: Henry was probably
the smartest man I ever met.

07:10.014 --> 07:11.265
He could have been
a nuclear physicist,

07:11.432 --> 07:12.767
he could have been
a Supreme Court judge,

07:12.934 --> 07:14.054
he could have been anything.

07:14.185 --> 07:17.146
Kelly: I remember the first time
Henry met my first wife.

07:17.313 --> 07:20.066
Afterwards she said,
"I've met Holden Caulfield."

07:21.609 --> 07:23.069
Henry Beard: My father
had graduated from Yale,

07:23.236 --> 07:25.488
and as a...
a bit of youthful rebellion,

07:25.655 --> 07:26.990
I decided to go to Harvard.

07:27.782 --> 07:31.035
Henry is about as private
a person as you'll ever find.

07:31.202 --> 07:34.247
He was mysterious and elusive.

07:34.580 --> 07:38.167
The two of them together were
an absolutely amazing team.

07:38.334 --> 07:40.837
When I was at Harvard,
we got a call one day

07:41.003 --> 07:42.505
from Betsy Talbot Blackwell,

07:42.672 --> 07:45.716
who was the editor-in-chief
of Mademoiselle magazine.

07:48.010 --> 07:50.346
She had seen a parody issue

07:50.513 --> 07:52.181
that the Harvard Lampoon
had put out,

07:52.348 --> 07:54.225
and Betsy said,
"You know, maybe I should"

07:54.392 --> 07:56.644
"ask these guys
to do a parody of us,"

07:56.811 --> 07:59.063
"and we'll publish it
in our own magazine."

07:59.480 --> 08:03.693
She offered us $7,000 which
seemed like nothing even then,

08:03.860 --> 08:07.613
but what she also offered was
a free subscription ad.

08:09.782 --> 08:12.910
We could do anything we wanted
as long as we put the clothes in

08:13.244 --> 08:15.371
and as long as we showed
the models,

08:15.538 --> 08:18.124
which, of course,
led to a lot of good times.

08:19.584 --> 08:21.586
And as a result of that
parody issue,

08:21.752 --> 08:24.547
we got tens of thousands
of subscriptions right away.

08:24.964 --> 08:26.299
She gave us a national audience.

08:28.342 --> 08:30.261
The discovery is that,
rather than having

08:30.428 --> 08:34.347
to depend on Mademoiselle to
make our magazines go national...

08:36.808 --> 08:40.520
...the Harvard Lampoon could actually
publish national magazines itself.

08:40.688 --> 08:43.649
They did Time magazine,
and they did Sports Illustrated

08:43.816 --> 08:45.443
and they did Life magazine.

08:45.610 --> 08:48.905
Beard: Doug Kenney and I decided
to do a parody of Lord of the Rings.

08:49.739 --> 08:51.699
We sent a letter to Tolkien,
who, honest to God,

08:51.866 --> 08:54.535
sent a letter back saying, "Yeah
go right ahead, silly book."

08:54.869 --> 08:57.288
I like the Playboy parody
that they did

08:57.371 --> 09:02.126
where the centerfold girl was more
tan around her bottom and top.

09:02.835 --> 09:04.420
She had reversed tan lines.

09:06.297 --> 09:08.049
Playboy was
a big hit nationally,

09:08.216 --> 09:10.760
and Doug and Henry realized
that maybe there was some way

09:10.927 --> 09:13.429
that the National Lampoon
could exist.

09:16.265 --> 09:18.601
Radio Announcer: Uh-uh-uh,
don't touch that dial.

09:18.768 --> 09:20.937
The National Lampoon
will be right back

09:21.103 --> 09:23.231
after this insincere
commercial message

09:23.397 --> 09:25.191
written by some cynical Nazis,

09:25.358 --> 09:28.027
solely for the purpose of
ripping off your parents' money.

09:29.362 --> 09:31.489
I think if you take yourself
back to when you were

09:31.656 --> 09:35.201
in your 20s, all possibilities
appear open to anybody.

09:35.368 --> 09:38.079
You know, you could
go after anything at any time.

09:39.872 --> 09:42.750
P.J. O'Rourke: Doug and Henry
had gone to New York

09:42.917 --> 09:45.795
in hopes of doing a 50/50 deal
with some publishing group

09:45.962 --> 09:47.797
who would put up the money.

09:48.714 --> 09:51.175
See, we met with some guys
from Time and Life.

09:51.342 --> 09:53.636
I can't tell you how
off-putting they were.

09:53.803 --> 09:56.180
Just saying, "Oh, you guys,
you don't understand anything."

09:56.347 --> 09:58.307
"You don't have a chance.
You're toast."

09:58.474 --> 09:59.795
"You're just not going anywhere."

10:00.351 --> 10:02.853
Doug Kenney was not
very happy about that

10:03.020 --> 10:05.189
and said, "You people are
the kind of people"

10:05.356 --> 10:07.608
"who commute back and forth
from Westport, Connecticut,"

10:07.775 --> 10:08.859
"in a station wagon."

10:09.568 --> 10:11.028
"We have nothing to do
with you."

10:11.195 --> 10:13.656
I thought, "Holy God",
but he was right!

10:14.365 --> 10:16.784
And that's how we ran
into 21 st Century Communications

10:16.951 --> 10:18.202
and Matty Simmons.

10:18.369 --> 10:20.871
Matty Simmons: Doug Kenney,
Henry Beard, and Rob Hoffman,

10:21.038 --> 10:23.082
three Harvard Lampoon editors,

10:23.249 --> 10:26.669
came into my office,
and I was immediately impressed.

10:30.214 --> 10:32.717
Matty belonged
to another generation.

10:32.883 --> 10:35.803
Very much New York,
very much old-school publishing.

10:35.970 --> 10:37.170
Ellis Weiner:
This guy invented

10:37.263 --> 10:39.423
the Diners' Club card,
which was the first credit card.

10:39.557 --> 10:41.434
Jams Hirsch: I think he wished
he was in the Rat Pack.

10:41.600 --> 10:43.436
He, sort of,
always had those bedroom eyes.

10:43.602 --> 10:45.271
You'd be talking to him
about something serious,

10:45.438 --> 10:46.564
and he'd take a phone call and say,

10:46.731 --> 10:49.483
"Oh, yeah, darling, baby,
I love you so much, I love you.

10:49.650 --> 10:52.051
Yeah, broccoli for dinner's fine.
Yeah, thank you, good-bye."

10:52.653 --> 10:55.865
Beard: He was very full of himself,
knew the business inside out.

10:56.032 --> 10:58.492
Distribution in those days was,
you know,

10:58.659 --> 11:00.036
there were some
criminal elements.

11:00.202 --> 11:02.843
Matty wasn't one of them, but he
had to deal with people like that.

11:05.624 --> 11:07.793
O'Rourke:
Magazines in the late '60s

11:07.960 --> 11:11.005
were thought to take about five years
before they got into the black.

11:11.172 --> 11:14.467
Rob intuited that this would
either work or it wouldn't.

11:14.633 --> 11:17.302
So he made a bet
when he negotiated the deal.

11:17.470 --> 11:19.388
He did a forced buyout
after five years.

11:19.555 --> 11:21.349
It was, kind of, a gutsy move.

11:21.515 --> 11:24.101
Simmons:
They owned 25%, I owned 75%.

11:24.268 --> 11:26.687
And part of the deal was,
after five years,

11:26.812 --> 11:28.272
I would buy them out.

11:28.439 --> 11:29.940
If this magazine is successful,

11:30.107 --> 11:33.736
I might owe these guys five,
six million dollars,

11:33.903 --> 11:35.071
but I made the deal.

11:36.364 --> 11:38.407
And we started National Lampoon.

11:43.496 --> 11:45.373
Their first hire was
Michael O'Donoghue,

11:45.539 --> 11:47.500
and Michael O'Donoghue
was not Harvard,

11:47.666 --> 11:49.460
Michael O'Donoghue was Buffalo.

11:49.960 --> 11:52.281
[music] (T. Rex "Children of
the Revolution" plays) [music]

11:57.259 --> 11:58.928
Boy, was he an angry bunny.

12:00.930 --> 12:05.267
He probably as much as anyone
gave the Lampoon its tone.

12:05.601 --> 12:07.978
We're doing this in place
of hitting you in the face.

12:08.145 --> 12:11.440
He had this recipe box,
you know the ones that ladies have

12:11.607 --> 12:13.067
with the recipes in them?

12:13.234 --> 12:15.194
"Oh, baked beans..."

12:16.070 --> 12:20.783
But his recipe box was full of things
like battling buses of World War ll.

12:20.950 --> 12:22.493
He just had
hundreds of these things.

12:23.702 --> 12:25.143
Chris Cerf:
He would take any chance.

12:25.162 --> 12:28.082
Even though we were perfectly
happy to do tasteful things,

12:28.249 --> 12:30.292
he pushed the bounds
even further.

12:30.459 --> 12:32.044
Doug did the dirty stuff,
Henry did the brainy stuff,

12:32.211 --> 12:33.771
and O'Donoghue did
the outrageous stuff,

12:33.921 --> 12:35.214
the really transgressive stuff.

12:50.771 --> 12:52.731
Tony Hendra was a British comic

12:52.898 --> 12:55.192
as part of a comedy team
called Ullett and Hendra.

12:55.359 --> 12:58.445
He and his partner Nick Ullett
used to be on The Merv Griffin Show.

12:58.612 --> 13:01.866
When you hear the buzz,
it will be the correct time.

13:02.366 --> 13:03.993
(buzzes)

13:04.160 --> 13:05.744
It is now the correct time.

13:05.911 --> 13:07.037
(audience laughing)

13:07.204 --> 13:09.373
Tony Hendra: Writing for television
was like firing on one cylinder.

13:09.540 --> 13:13.961
Working at the Lampoon was like
firing on all six cylinders.

13:14.128 --> 13:16.338
It was like you could talk about
anything you wanted.

13:16.505 --> 13:18.674
There was absolutely
nothing that was,

13:18.841 --> 13:21.302
"You can't say that, Tony"
or "That's not funny, Tony."

13:21.469 --> 13:24.138
He had this extraordinarily
educated-at-Cambridge accent

13:24.305 --> 13:26.015
and was very literate
and worldly

13:26.182 --> 13:29.935
and yet behaved like
a delinquent of 12 or 13.

13:41.030 --> 13:43.115
I was a humble Canadian
schoolteacher.

13:43.282 --> 13:46.160
One day, my upstairs neighbor,
Michel Choquette,

13:46.327 --> 13:49.371
came home and told me he was
interested in starting to write

13:49.538 --> 13:51.540
for this National Lampoon
magazine

13:51.707 --> 13:53.209
that was being
started in New York.

13:53.375 --> 13:55.711
I thought, well, maybe I can
come down to New York

13:55.878 --> 13:57.254
and become rich and famous

13:57.421 --> 14:00.132
and get tremendous amounts
of drugs and sex and things.

14:00.925 --> 14:02.426
None of which panned out.

14:11.060 --> 14:13.145
Sean Kelly actually fixed me up

14:13.270 --> 14:15.147
on a blind date
with Michel Choquette.

14:15.481 --> 14:18.818
And then Michel started
taking me to New York with him

14:18.984 --> 14:22.071
because I was, quote unquote,
"Helping him with his work."

14:23.447 --> 14:25.199
I got into comedy the same way

14:25.366 --> 14:27.701
that Catherine the Great
got into politics

14:28.202 --> 14:29.286
on my back.

14:39.547 --> 14:43.051
I was working in a saloon
on the West Side.

14:43.217 --> 14:45.219
One night,
somebody came over to me.

14:45.386 --> 14:47.721
"There's a fellow back there
stealing the ketchup."

14:47.888 --> 14:48.931
And I go after him, and I said,

14:49.098 --> 14:50.578
"Excuse me,
I know what you're doing."

14:50.641 --> 14:52.762
And then I realize I'm standing
here accusing somebody

14:52.851 --> 14:56.105
of stealing ketchup
from a red rubber bottle.

14:56.397 --> 14:57.899
So this is so sad.

14:58.399 --> 15:00.693
Very shortly thereafter,
Henry offered me a job,

15:00.859 --> 15:02.152
and I gleefully took it.

15:04.572 --> 15:06.574
Doug and Henry had this idea
about bringing in

15:06.740 --> 15:10.661
this very hippie-ish
art studio called Cloud.

15:17.293 --> 15:20.296
Cloud Studios was
an independent design firm.

15:21.088 --> 15:23.382
That's a generous term to use
for those guys.

15:23.549 --> 15:25.217
Bill Skurski: We were,
quote unquote, "hippie artists"

15:25.384 --> 15:26.719
because we weren't out
to be millionaires.

15:26.885 --> 15:28.679
We were out to do
the things we liked to do.

15:29.430 --> 15:30.550
You know, we were turned on,

15:30.598 --> 15:32.975
and I don't mean by drugs,
I mean by the ideas.

15:35.227 --> 15:38.480
Doug liked to hang with people
like Cloud Studio artists.

15:38.647 --> 15:40.524
He like the fact
that they were kind of freaky

15:40.691 --> 15:43.152
and wore costumes
and had beards.

15:43.569 --> 15:45.362
Michael Sullivan: Doug would
come to parties that we had,

15:45.529 --> 15:48.616
and when Doug wasn't in
the office working,

15:48.782 --> 15:50.743
he was probably high as a kite.

15:50.909 --> 15:53.370
Kelly: Doug wanted to be
a beat or a hippie.

15:53.537 --> 15:56.081
Doug wanted to be trendy
and with it.

15:56.457 --> 16:00.169
I remember Doug asking, "Should I...
Should I be for the Black Panthers?"

16:00.753 --> 16:01.879
And he wasn't kidding.

16:08.510 --> 16:10.929
I saw the first issue, um,
which was terrible.

16:14.183 --> 16:15.393
Sam Gross: They had this duck.

16:15.559 --> 16:19.688
And they were gonna keep
the duck as a logo on the cover

16:19.855 --> 16:21.815
like the Playboy bunny.

16:21.982 --> 16:24.818
I said to Henry,
"Get rid of the duck."

16:24.985 --> 16:26.820
That's not the Playboy bunny
where, you know,

16:26.987 --> 16:30.783
you can put it on a garter,
make it a pasty or whatever.

16:31.158 --> 16:34.203
Everything they did was,
it had to be funny-looking,

16:34.370 --> 16:37.247
which means it was all sort of
squirrely and hippie-like.

16:40.751 --> 16:44.338
The issues were messy,
they were confusing.

16:44.505 --> 16:46.173
It wasn't bringing in
the readers,

16:46.340 --> 16:48.381
and they weren't getting
the sales on the newsstand.

16:49.051 --> 16:51.345
I told them, "We've gotta
replace your art director."

16:53.681 --> 16:56.183
Doug was very upset,
he wanted to keep Cloud,

16:56.350 --> 17:00.229
and he argued with me,
but it was my call, I was the boss.

17:01.146 --> 17:04.483
After we did the first seven issues,
I got a call from Doug Kenney.

17:04.650 --> 17:07.569
He said, "I'm sorry, but you're
no longer the art director."

17:07.736 --> 17:10.196
Great, knock yourself out.

17:22.584 --> 17:25.253
When I brought Michael Gross in,
Doug was kinda hostile.

17:25.421 --> 17:27.673
My first issue when
I walked in the door

17:27.839 --> 17:32.886
was the nostalgia issue,
which was Doug Kenney's baby.

17:41.729 --> 17:44.941
I knew when I was hired,
I was hired against Doug's will.

17:45.232 --> 17:47.276
In the sales pitch that I made,

17:47.443 --> 17:51.781
I referred to an article they'd
done about postage stamps.

17:51.947 --> 17:57.161
I said, "For these stamps to work,
they should look like real stamps."

18:00.372 --> 18:02.666
You should be fooled
when you look at them.

18:02.833 --> 18:06.336
Therefore the parody
is empowered.

18:06.503 --> 18:10.924
And in that little example,
he transformed the magazine.

18:13.594 --> 18:16.305
After that, Doug came
into my office and said,

18:16.472 --> 18:18.056
"You were right about this guy."

18:18.766 --> 18:21.810
As soon as Michael came aboard,
the Lampoon began to look great.

18:22.227 --> 18:25.063
[music] (King Floyd's
"Groove Me" plays) [music]

18:39.536 --> 18:41.955
Cerf: And what the Lampoon
began to be able to do

18:42.122 --> 18:45.042
was to create anything
in any format,

18:45.209 --> 18:47.419
so that it looked like the original.

18:59.681 --> 19:01.558
Michael O'Donoghue: You know,
Ed Sullivan, we kid him a lot,

19:01.725 --> 19:04.144
but Ed Sullivan is one of
the greats of this business,

19:04.311 --> 19:06.230
and I had a funny thought.

19:06.605 --> 19:12.027
What if Ed Sullivan were tortured,
and when I say tortured,

19:12.194 --> 19:14.947
what I mean is,
what if steel needles,

19:15.113 --> 19:18.450
say six inches long,
were plunged into Ed's eyes?

19:18.617 --> 19:21.245
I... I think it would go
something like this...

19:21.411 --> 19:25.833
(continuous screaming)

19:31.338 --> 19:34.132
You could walk into
the Lampoon editorial office

19:34.299 --> 19:35.884
and get high just walking in.

19:36.343 --> 19:38.720
But as long as it stayed
in the editorial office,

19:38.887 --> 19:41.098
and as long as they were doing
the terrific work

19:41.265 --> 19:43.976
they were doing,
I didn't tell them what to do.

19:46.311 --> 19:48.355
In the course of a given day,
it was understood

19:48.522 --> 19:52.609
that the day didn't end
when the office day ended.

19:52.776 --> 19:55.153
Beatts: They would have these
dinner meetings in, like,

19:55.320 --> 19:57.155
some of the worst restaurants
in New York.

19:57.322 --> 19:59.643
Brian McConnachie: There was
a saloon called The Green Man.

19:59.700 --> 20:04.037
It was hot,
it smelled of cat stink.

20:04.204 --> 20:07.249
And they would sit around a table
and drink tons and tons of beer.

20:07.416 --> 20:09.418
This would be paid for
by Henry or Doug.

20:09.585 --> 20:11.837
They would whip out their
company American Express card

20:12.004 --> 20:13.255
and pay for dinner.

20:13.422 --> 20:15.424
That's when we made up
the next issue.

20:15.591 --> 20:19.928
You had to either get Doug or Henry
to react positively to your idea.

20:20.512 --> 20:22.139
Ed Subhzky: The ideas would
come out very rapid fire.

20:22.306 --> 20:23.390
"How did he think of that?"
And then...

20:23.557 --> 20:24.808
"How did he think of that?"

20:25.017 --> 20:26.393
"How did he think of that?"

20:29.104 --> 20:30.981
We all do it the same way,
you get drunk,

20:31.398 --> 20:33.650
you go home,
you get up in the morning,

20:33.817 --> 20:35.027
and you write the piece.

20:35.319 --> 20:37.738
Gross: Doug was who
you went to really see

20:37.905 --> 20:41.199
if you had some wild and wacky
brilliant but funny idea.

20:41.742 --> 20:44.161
Doug would go,
"I gotcha, you're in."

20:44.328 --> 20:45.688
Beard: I mean,
he was a workaholic.

20:45.746 --> 20:47.748
I mean,
he was unbelievably productive.

20:47.915 --> 20:50.584
Like, he wrote
the Letters column every month.

20:50.751 --> 20:53.170
I mean, that's like 2200
very funny words of letters

20:53.337 --> 20:54.838
in, like, an hour and a half.

20:55.005 --> 20:57.216
I mean, every single time
there was something

20:57.382 --> 21:00.177
that had to be done,
he really was focused on it.

21:00.761 --> 21:02.429
Shary Flenniken:
Doug was valuable in that sense.

21:02.596 --> 21:05.265
Because he would
stimulate your ideas.

21:05.432 --> 21:08.226
So I don't think that there
really was anyone else

21:08.352 --> 21:10.771
who could inspire
other people like Doug.

21:11.104 --> 21:13.065
People would come
to Henry with ideas,

21:13.231 --> 21:14.691
and Henry would say,

21:15.192 --> 21:16.693
"Tempting, tempting."

21:16.860 --> 21:20.447
Whatever idea you pitched him,
he would say, "Tempting, tempting."

21:20.614 --> 21:22.658
"Tempting" meant that

21:22.783 --> 21:25.035
that is so awful,
it really blows chunks.

21:25.410 --> 21:28.747
Or, I'm about to have
an intellectual orgasm, it's so good.

21:29.498 --> 21:31.625
Subhzky: Somehow Henry Beard
would take this ragtag

21:31.792 --> 21:34.419
bunch of material and different
types of personalities

21:34.586 --> 21:36.338
and brilliantly
merge it together

21:36.505 --> 21:38.966
to make a magazine that was
surprisingly coherent.

21:39.132 --> 21:41.453
[music] (Dave Mason
"Only You Know & I Know" plays) [music]

21:53.063 --> 21:56.567
Beard: It was like we had
an attic full of culture

21:57.234 --> 22:01.780
that had been accumulating
from 1945 to 1970.

22:02.030 --> 22:05.659
And we opened the trap door,
and nobody had been up there,

22:06.410 --> 22:08.412
and we just basically looted it.

22:10.539 --> 22:12.791
Kelly: Michael O'Donoghue's
Vietnamese Baby Book

22:12.958 --> 22:15.669
was an extraordinary
piece of satire.

22:15.836 --> 22:19.548
It was a baby book, but it was
designed to be for a Vietnamese baby,

22:19.715 --> 22:22.759
and so it had things in it like
"Baby's First Wound."

22:24.511 --> 22:26.054
(laughing)

22:29.099 --> 22:31.351
Simmons:
It was incredibly dark,

22:31.601 --> 22:35.063
extremely political,
and it was funny.

22:36.982 --> 22:39.192
Michel Choquette came to me
with an idea.

22:39.359 --> 22:42.654
He had run into a guy who looked
just like Adolf Hitler.

22:43.196 --> 22:46.366
Flenniken: The piece was called
Stranger in Paradise

22:46.700 --> 22:50.912
which was about Adolf Hitler
really survived World War Two

22:51.121 --> 22:55.167
and was living on a tropical island
somewhere in the Caribbean.

22:56.585 --> 22:59.004
Simmons: I gave him a budget,
and ten days later

22:59.129 --> 23:00.631
I got a telegram, it said,

23:00.839 --> 23:04.009
"Hitler eating too much,
need more money."

23:04.176 --> 23:08.097
I said, "Stop feeding Hitler
and return to New York immediately."

23:08.263 --> 23:09.681
And it was a brilliant article,

23:09.848 --> 23:13.018
which we resold to almost
every foreign country.

23:16.021 --> 23:18.815
Doug Kenney came up with
the photo funnies concept.

23:18.982 --> 23:23.737
Doug insisted that they be us
and some girls we brought in.

23:23.904 --> 23:26.740
I was so opposed.
"Guys, we're a real magazine.

23:26.907 --> 23:29.493
We don't need to take Polaroid's
in a fuckin' office."

23:30.243 --> 23:33.496
I was so wrong,
because what Doug recognized

23:33.663 --> 23:37.084
is the audience identified with us.

23:37.876 --> 23:40.462
They went, "These are, like,
a bunch of jerk-offs like me."

23:40.629 --> 23:42.714
Like, "You and me,
Bernie, look!"

23:43.548 --> 23:46.009
That's Doug Kenney's genius.

23:47.135 --> 23:50.388
They did probably one of the greatest
magazine covers ever done.

23:50.555 --> 23:53.308
Beard: Ed Bluestone came
to the office, and he said,

23:53.475 --> 23:54.976
"You're gonna get a dog,"

23:55.143 --> 23:56.686
"gonna put a pistol to its head,
and you're gonna say"

23:56.853 --> 23:59.014
" 'If you don't buy this magazine,
we'll kill this dog...'"

23:59.106 --> 24:01.547
I said, "Ed, that's the most
brilliant thing I've ever heard."

24:01.900 --> 24:04.194
Gross:
It was a huge, huge hit

24:04.361 --> 24:08.698
because it's what every magazine
publisher wanted to do.

24:08.865 --> 24:11.284
All they want to say is,
"Buy the fucking magazine!"

24:19.251 --> 24:22.045
We realized that artists,
well-known established artists,

24:22.212 --> 24:25.590
people like Arnold Roth,
the great cartoonist Gahan Wilson,

24:27.050 --> 24:28.301
Sam Gross.

24:32.055 --> 24:34.182
Charlotte Rodriguez is
just a wonderful illustrator.

24:34.349 --> 24:35.642
Neal Adams.

24:35.809 --> 24:40.105
They all had to have
drawers full of wonderful stuff

24:40.272 --> 24:43.692
that had been rejected by
more traditional publications

24:43.859 --> 24:45.569
that weren't rejected because
they weren't funny or good,

24:45.735 --> 24:47.320
they were rejected because
they were a little too raunchy,

24:47.487 --> 24:49.322
so we knew we were that outlet.

24:49.489 --> 24:51.408
It didn't matter
how strange your work was.

24:51.575 --> 24:54.661
It didn't matter if your work
was anti-republican,

24:54.870 --> 24:56.746
anti-democrat,
anti-the-universe,

24:56.913 --> 24:58.874
whatever it was,
you could bring it into them,

24:59.040 --> 25:00.750
and they would not touch it.

25:01.168 --> 25:02.627
And that's one great thing
about the Lampoon.

25:02.794 --> 25:04.629
Never before and never
since had that kind of freedom.

25:04.796 --> 25:06.423
Gross:
If you were smart and funny,

25:06.590 --> 25:10.218
you walked into Henry Beard's office
or Doug Kenney's office,

25:10.385 --> 25:12.345
"Hello, can I come
show you some stuff?"

25:12.470 --> 25:15.031
He goes like this, he goes,
"Brilliant, thank you, you're hired."

25:15.056 --> 25:17.726
"We don't pay much,
but we're not gonna edit you."

25:17.893 --> 25:19.269
"We're not going to change you."

25:19.436 --> 25:21.855
"We're gonna let you be
what you want to be."

25:28.236 --> 25:29.571
We had one problem.

25:30.197 --> 25:31.656
It was losing a lot of money.

25:33.158 --> 25:34.659
Because we couldn't get advertising.

25:37.412 --> 25:39.492
Jerry Taylor: They sold little,
teeny mail order ads.

25:43.793 --> 25:48.715
They needed a pro to come in,
make it bigger, more legitimate.

25:50.717 --> 25:52.886
Danny Abelson: Jerry Taylor was
an extraordinarily successful

25:53.053 --> 25:54.930
and, sort of,
charismatic ad guy.

25:55.347 --> 25:57.547
Bill Lippe: We had a difficult
time getting appointments

25:57.599 --> 25:59.351
with advertising prospects.

25:59.643 --> 26:02.437
Taylor: It was always hard
to be taken seriously,

26:03.104 --> 26:04.981
so I had a dress code.

26:05.565 --> 26:08.485
Three piece suit,
white shirt, vest, tie.

26:08.652 --> 26:11.112
We walked in looking exactly
like the guys from Time Inc.

26:12.113 --> 26:15.825
But still nothing,
zero, nothing mattered.

26:16.409 --> 26:21.331
It was almost like they would
vomit up this hostility on the desk.

26:22.082 --> 26:24.292
And I would say,
"Okay, that's cool."

26:24.459 --> 26:25.900
"You don't have to buy
a subscription,"

26:25.919 --> 26:28.672
"but now let me tell you
why I think our audience"

26:28.838 --> 26:31.549
"is a great target for
your product."

26:32.050 --> 26:36.388
Our readership drank more than
the average adult.

26:36.554 --> 26:39.140
And the first liquor
advertisement that we had

26:39.307 --> 26:40.725
at the magazine was Jose Cuervo,

26:40.892 --> 26:42.727
and it made other people,
"Oh, wow,

26:42.894 --> 26:44.896
they got a liquor advertisement
in the Lampoon."

26:45.063 --> 26:46.731
And then the snowball started.

26:46.982 --> 26:49.276
[music] (King Floyd's
"Groove Me" plays) [music]

27:01.454 --> 27:03.373
Taylor: I had a slogan,
"National Lampoon.

27:03.748 --> 27:06.334
There's nothing funny about
the way it sells."

27:16.011 --> 27:19.014
Tell me about National Lampoon.
Why do you think it's so popular?

27:19.180 --> 27:21.016
Well, I think they're very witty.

27:21.182 --> 27:24.019
Yes, they're very witty,
but they are designed

27:24.185 --> 27:26.479
to please and flatter

27:26.646 --> 27:31.067
a particular audience of
fairly well-to-do nobodies

27:31.276 --> 27:33.153
who can afford to be nobodies.

27:33.320 --> 27:38.491
[music] (Pacific Gas & Electric
"Are You Ready?" plays) [music]

27:49.377 --> 27:52.130
I honestly think that
the National Lampoon

27:52.297 --> 27:54.674
is the most entertaining
magazine I have ever read.

27:54.758 --> 27:56.760
It's often the only
magazine that a lot of

27:56.926 --> 28:00.221
younger, hip people
today, uh, read.

28:00.388 --> 28:04.059
And why that is,
is I think they trust us.

28:04.225 --> 28:06.436
[music] (music continues) [music]

28:06.603 --> 28:08.323
It looks really good,
it's funny to look at.

28:08.396 --> 28:11.107
It's weird to look at.
And if you read the printed stuff,

28:11.274 --> 28:12.776
if you look at things
that aren't the pictures,

28:12.942 --> 28:14.652
occasionally you find
something really good

28:14.819 --> 28:17.220
which you don't find anywhere
else in the written humor form.

28:17.530 --> 28:19.366
There was a lot
of bad stuff going on.

28:20.700 --> 28:22.327
Christopher Buckley: We'd just
come out of the sixties.

28:22.494 --> 28:25.497
We had the assassinations,
Vietnam, now we had Watergate.

28:25.663 --> 28:32.378
So it was a perfect storm moment
of brilliant comic sensibilities

28:32.670 --> 28:35.673
hitting the culture
in a crisis point.

28:37.258 --> 28:39.886
Thornton: It was actually
the first time that I realized

28:40.053 --> 28:42.680
that, through humor,
you can tell the truth.

28:48.853 --> 28:50.522
Apatow:
In a mass media way,

28:50.688 --> 28:52.690
this kind of comedy didn't
exist before then.

28:52.857 --> 28:54.359
People weren't that frank

28:54.526 --> 28:58.071
and didn't attack the
establishment comedically.

28:58.238 --> 28:59.573
Beard: We're basically
a humor magazine,

28:59.739 --> 29:01.282
and we publish things
we consider to be funny.

29:01.449 --> 29:03.493
It's just impossible to put out
this kind of a publication

29:03.660 --> 29:08.289
and be, uh, completely unwilling
to do something offensive.

29:08.456 --> 29:09.916
I think it's sometimes conscious

29:10.083 --> 29:12.544
and sometimes just instinctive
that we push things

29:12.710 --> 29:14.629
as far as they possibly
can be pushed.

29:14.796 --> 29:16.036
I've always had a bad attitude.

29:16.089 --> 29:17.090
Interviewer: Always?

29:17.257 --> 29:19.426
I'm earning a living off
a bad attitude right now.

29:19.592 --> 29:20.927
Teachers always said
it would get me in trouble,

29:21.052 --> 29:22.453
but it's great,
it's working for me.

29:26.599 --> 29:28.560
In those days,
magazines were a bigger deal.

29:29.978 --> 29:34.441
People very much defined themselves
by the magazines they read.

29:38.111 --> 29:39.487
Simmons:
It was the most popular magazine

29:39.654 --> 29:41.406
on college campuses in America

29:41.573 --> 29:44.075
and was the second
most popular magazine

29:44.242 --> 29:47.871
on newsstands in America,
second only to Cosmopolitan.

29:50.623 --> 29:53.209
The biggest circulation
we ever had was a million.

29:53.376 --> 29:57.172
We had a pass along
of maybe 12 or 15.

29:57.589 --> 30:01.927
So we probably had
12 million readers.

30:02.093 --> 30:03.803
I mean, it was huge.

30:03.970 --> 30:05.930
It's our unerring charm
that makes our readers

30:06.097 --> 30:07.557
swallow it month after month.

30:07.724 --> 30:09.893
And frankly, that's what
it's all about, isn't it?

30:10.977 --> 30:13.730
Suddenly Doug Kenney disappeared.

30:16.441 --> 30:19.611
When Doug left or disappeared,

30:20.236 --> 30:22.697
it was...
It was a crisis.

30:22.864 --> 30:24.866
One Sunday morning
I came downstairs,

30:25.033 --> 30:26.743
and there was a note
in the kitchen, and it said,

30:26.910 --> 30:28.786
"Henry, I'm gonzo.

30:28.953 --> 30:30.997
I'm out of here, I'm gone,
I'm finished, I'm done."

30:31.623 --> 30:32.624
And he was gone.

30:40.173 --> 30:43.593
Radio Announcer: And now the
final question, for $25,000.

30:43.718 --> 30:45.762
Name four famous Mickeys.

30:47.305 --> 30:49.891
Man: Uh, Mickey Mouse.

30:50.391 --> 30:51.752
Radio Announcer:
That's number one.

30:51.893 --> 30:53.144
Man: Mickey, Mickey Mantle.

30:53.603 --> 30:54.854
Radio Announcer: Number two.

30:55.772 --> 30:58.691
Man: Uh, Mickey Rooney.

30:58.775 --> 30:59.901
Radio Announcer:
That's number three.

31:00.026 --> 31:02.362
Only one more,
and you win $25,000.

31:04.030 --> 31:05.198
Man: Mickey Way.

31:06.741 --> 31:07.909
Radio Announcer: Mickey Way?

31:08.826 --> 31:10.328
Man: The candy bar,
they'll take that, won't they?

31:10.495 --> 31:12.664
- The judges will take that?
- (buzzer sounding)

31:13.414 --> 31:16.918
Because I had had a previous career
as half of a comedy team,

31:17.085 --> 31:20.547
I had experience in how to write
and put together an album.

31:20.713 --> 31:24.300
And I was paired with O'Donoghue,
who wanted to do this album,

31:24.467 --> 31:26.719
so that's how
Radio Dinner came to be.

31:27.512 --> 31:30.598
Kelly: But the album itself was
very much Michael O'Donoghue.

31:30.974 --> 31:33.602
So Michael would say, "TV dinner?
What about radio dinner?"

31:33.768 --> 31:36.312
And then he'd go, "Yes," and
he'd write down Radio Dinner.

31:36.479 --> 31:38.189
And a year later
when someone said,

31:38.356 --> 31:39.857
"Let's do an album," he'd go...

31:40.858 --> 31:42.235
"Let's call it Radio Dinner."

31:43.236 --> 31:45.739
Cerf: Still one of my favorites
was a parody song

31:45.905 --> 31:47.865
that Michael O'Donoghue
and I wrote

31:48.032 --> 31:49.909
and that Tony Hendra
ended up performing,

31:50.076 --> 31:51.536
brilliantly, I might add.

31:51.786 --> 31:53.413
[music] I resent performing
for you fuckers [music]

31:53.580 --> 31:54.873
[music] Tell me,
what do you know? [music]

31:55.039 --> 31:56.666
[music] A lot of faggot
middle class kids [music]

31:56.833 --> 31:58.418
[music] Wearing long hair
and trendy clothes [music]

31:58.585 --> 32:00.128
[music] I don't owe you fuckers
anything [music]

32:00.295 --> 32:02.714
[music] And all I've got
to say is fuck you... [music]

32:02.880 --> 32:04.281
Cerf:
It was right after John Lennon

32:04.382 --> 32:06.509
had an interview in Rolling Stone,

32:06.676 --> 32:10.555
and we had the idea that if you just
put in an occasional rhyme...

32:10.722 --> 32:13.642
[music] The sky is blue... [music]

32:13.975 --> 32:16.269
You could set the whole
interview to music.

32:16.436 --> 32:18.062
[music] George said
she gave off evil vibes [music]

32:18.229 --> 32:20.314
[music] I should have beat the fucking
shit right out of him [music]

32:20.481 --> 32:24.527
[music] Him with his
fucking Hare Krishna [music]

32:26.863 --> 32:28.703
Hendra: The album was actually
a great success.

32:28.865 --> 32:30.346
It got a tremendous amount
of airplay.

32:30.491 --> 32:31.993
It was also
nominated for a Grammy,

32:32.160 --> 32:33.640
which was pretty good,
first time out.

32:33.745 --> 32:37.123
It showed that we could more
than simply put out a magazine.

32:39.959 --> 32:41.878
The truth is,
Doug carried the magazine.

32:42.045 --> 32:45.590
If I wrote a hundred words,
he wrote a thousand, every month.

32:45.757 --> 32:48.259
People hadn't really expected
that he would disappear,

32:48.426 --> 32:50.720
but Doug was
not a stable person.

32:51.012 --> 32:52.263
Beard:
He had an older brother

32:52.388 --> 32:54.109
who was the preferred son,
the favorite son,

32:54.515 --> 32:56.976
and his older brother
died at an early age,

32:57.143 --> 32:58.853
and it was a great loss
to his parents,

32:59.020 --> 33:01.481
and his parents, kind of,
treated Doug as the...

33:01.648 --> 33:03.984
As the "Well, I guess
that's all we've got left."

33:04.359 --> 33:07.153
It probably did have
some emotional impact on him.

33:07.445 --> 33:10.006
Gross: And basically what happened
is he had a nervous breakdown.

33:10.073 --> 33:12.283
And he just couldn't
take it anymore.

33:12.575 --> 33:13.951
John Weidman:
He needed a break.

33:14.118 --> 33:16.913
He was having sort of
a mid-life crisis

33:17.080 --> 33:18.456
at the age of 24, whatever.

33:18.581 --> 33:20.083
He was trying
to figure himself out,

33:20.291 --> 33:23.002
and he picked up and moved
to Martha's Vineyard.

33:24.087 --> 33:26.423
I think he wanted to try
something else before 30.

33:26.631 --> 33:28.257
He's got to do something new.

33:28.424 --> 33:31.260
Hendra: He wanted to write
Teenage Commies from Outer Space.

33:31.427 --> 33:34.263
I went up to Martha's Vineyard
to actually see Doug.

33:34.430 --> 33:38.893
My idea was to take stuff
and develop from the magazine

33:39.060 --> 33:41.479
and then put it on stage,
and then Matty said

33:41.646 --> 33:42.814
it needed Doug's touch.

33:42.980 --> 33:44.148
He looked completely wasted.

33:44.315 --> 33:47.235
He'd obviously been
dropping acid and eating very little.

33:48.069 --> 33:50.510
He wanted to go for a walk
'cause he had something to show me.

33:50.571 --> 33:52.824
And we walked out to where
there's this peculiar,

33:52.990 --> 33:55.284
kind of, mud which runs
right down to the sea.

33:55.451 --> 33:58.204
And he said
it was really groovy,

33:58.371 --> 34:01.999
really groovy in the summer
to slather yourself with this stuff

34:02.125 --> 34:03.209
and just lie in the sun.

34:04.836 --> 34:06.546
So I had pitched my idea,

34:06.713 --> 34:08.797
and he said,
"No, man, I can't do that.

34:08.965 --> 34:10.425
I'm too deep into my novel."

34:10.591 --> 34:13.344
And it turned he'd written
one and a half chapters.

34:17.181 --> 34:19.641
[music] Aah... [music]

34:23.396 --> 34:26.774
The first album did so well,
we've got to do another album.

34:26.940 --> 34:29.485
Wouldn't it be fun
to parody Woodstock?

34:29.652 --> 34:32.321
We were going to do
a three night show, record it,

34:32.487 --> 34:35.074
edit it, and that would be
the second album.

34:35.824 --> 34:38.161
But it got out of hand.

34:38.327 --> 34:39.688
[music] (rock music plays) [music]

34:39.829 --> 34:42.706
[music] We are Lemmings! [music]

34:42.873 --> 34:46.460
[music] (guitar riff plays) [music]

34:46.627 --> 34:49.505
We needed a cast of
people who could be very funny

34:49.672 --> 34:51.841
and could play an instrument

34:52.007 --> 34:54.761
or, at the very least,
sing extremely well.

34:54.927 --> 34:56.469
Simmons: Tony Hendra called me
one night, and he said,

34:56.637 --> 34:59.140
"There's a guy here
at Second City in Chicago,"

34:59.307 --> 35:02.685
"and he's the funniest actor
I've ever seen in my life."

35:02.852 --> 35:03.895
"He's incredible."

35:04.061 --> 35:05.479
So I said,
"Bring him to New York."

35:08.065 --> 35:09.567
John Belushi: Can I have
your attention please?

35:09.734 --> 35:12.695
The theme of Lemmings
Woodshuck Festival

35:12.862 --> 35:15.948
was that everyone's
come together to off themself.

35:16.115 --> 35:19.619
Lemmings are animals that commit
suicide by going over cliffs.

35:20.870 --> 35:23.706
So they were giving advice on how
they might do this along the way

35:23.873 --> 35:25.625
by the announcer, who was John.

35:25.792 --> 35:28.294
(applause)

35:28.461 --> 35:30.797
Now we all know
why we came here.

35:31.756 --> 35:33.299
A million of us,

35:33.925 --> 35:35.885
we came here to off ourselves.

35:36.052 --> 35:38.763
He made the character into this,
kind of,

35:38.930 --> 35:43.184
manically agreeable
murderous lunatic.

35:43.351 --> 35:45.144
If your buddy is too stoned
to off himself,

35:45.311 --> 35:46.687
do him a favor.

35:46.854 --> 35:48.815
Roll him up in his sleeping bag

35:48.981 --> 35:51.818
and drag him over to where
the tractors can run him down.

35:54.237 --> 35:58.157
Chris Guest did a James Taylor
that was genius.

35:58.324 --> 36:00.243
[music] Farewell,
New York City [music]

36:00.409 --> 36:03.787
[music] With your streets that
flash like strobes [music]

36:04.247 --> 36:06.499
[music] Farewell, Carolina [music]

36:06.749 --> 36:09.794
[music] Where I left
my frontal lobes [music]

36:09.961 --> 36:11.420
Hey! Chevy!

36:11.587 --> 36:13.005
Hey! What's your
name again?!

36:13.256 --> 36:15.633
- John.
- John, hey!

36:15.800 --> 36:17.719
Chevy Chase: There was a sketch
where John and I

36:17.885 --> 36:19.929
were two high school
or college guys

36:20.096 --> 36:21.848
at urinals, just talking.

36:21.973 --> 36:23.308
I can't even remember
what it was about,

36:23.474 --> 36:25.977
but I do remember that
they were laughing all through.

36:26.435 --> 36:28.354
And it became clearer
and clearer to me

36:28.479 --> 36:29.522
that they were laughing at John,

36:29.689 --> 36:30.857
whether he was saying
anything or not.

36:31.023 --> 36:32.024
(laughter)

36:32.108 --> 36:33.776
I'm like this, talking to John.

36:35.069 --> 36:38.614
And finally after, like, a week,
I have to look over at him

36:38.781 --> 36:40.449
to see what the hell
is going on,

36:40.616 --> 36:42.536
why are they always laughing?
And he's like this.

36:44.078 --> 36:47.039
(chuckling)

36:47.456 --> 36:49.083
Never knew it, never told me.

36:50.042 --> 36:52.253
The little bastard just took me.

36:52.420 --> 36:55.131
(laughing)

36:55.590 --> 36:56.799
It was so good.

36:57.967 --> 37:00.344
It was decided, because
the ticket sales were so brisk,

37:00.845 --> 37:02.445
that we would simply
leave the show open.

37:02.555 --> 37:04.765
And at that point,
from a record project,

37:04.932 --> 37:07.101
it actually become an
off-Broadway show.

37:07.685 --> 37:09.103
[music] (piano music plays) [music]

37:09.270 --> 37:12.064
It was in this little
tiny club in the Village,

37:12.231 --> 37:15.443
but it was an underground hit,
it was a cool thing to go see.

37:15.610 --> 37:16.903
(indistinct singing)
[music] Well I'm standing here [music]

37:17.069 --> 37:18.404
[music] Singing my song [music]

37:18.571 --> 37:22.283
[music] Well, there ain't nothing
to do, all my friends are gone [music]

37:22.783 --> 37:25.786
[music] I had sunshine
and a country home [music]

37:25.953 --> 37:28.873
[music] I've been on the cover
of Rolling Stone [music]

37:29.040 --> 37:31.042
- [music] But it lonely [music]
- [music] Yes it's lonely [music]

37:31.208 --> 37:32.877
Kelly:
When we were with the actors,

37:33.044 --> 37:34.754
it got more rambunctious.

37:34.921 --> 37:37.965
Because that was
when actual uppers and downers

37:38.132 --> 37:41.093
and nose candy,
and things, entered.

37:41.260 --> 37:43.387
What about the acid?
You gonna open the acid?

37:45.264 --> 37:46.349
What acid?

37:47.600 --> 37:49.602
What do you mean,
"What acid," John?

37:49.769 --> 37:51.520
- What acid?
- The LSD 25, man.

37:51.687 --> 37:53.230
You mean the LSD zero?

37:53.397 --> 37:54.941
(audience laughing)

37:55.107 --> 37:56.567
Tony would go to Matty and say

37:56.734 --> 38:00.446
he needed X bucks
to buy marijuana for the cast.

38:00.613 --> 38:03.407
And then Tony, of course, would
immediately buy cocaine with it.

38:03.908 --> 38:06.244
I mean, everybody can buy
their own marijuana.

38:07.078 --> 38:09.246
[music] (music continues) [music]

38:09.413 --> 38:10.581
(applause)

38:10.748 --> 38:12.833
Hey! Hey,
You gotta get up!

38:14.543 --> 38:16.462
Hup! Hup!

38:16.629 --> 38:19.423
(groaning)

38:23.135 --> 38:24.178
Whoa!

38:24.345 --> 38:25.930
(laughter)

38:29.016 --> 38:31.185
[music] What would you do [music]

38:31.852 --> 38:34.396
[music] If I sang out of tune? [music]

38:34.563 --> 38:37.817
- One, two, three!
- [music] Lonely at the bottom [music]

38:37.984 --> 38:40.278
[music] Lonely,
lonely, lonely [music]

38:40.444 --> 38:42.905
- [music] Lonely at the bottom [music]
- [music] I said my baby's lonely [music]

38:43.072 --> 38:44.699
[music] I said she lonely,
I said she lonely [music]

38:44.865 --> 38:47.451
[music] I said she lonely,
I said she lonely, I said... [music]

38:48.452 --> 38:50.121
(music stops)

38:50.287 --> 38:54.333
(cheering and applause)

38:54.667 --> 38:58.129
Gross: Henry Beard's
office door hardly ever opened.

38:58.462 --> 39:01.215
Henry Beard sat there and typed.

39:01.382 --> 39:02.758
(typewriter keys clicking)

39:02.925 --> 39:05.553
Pull it out, pull it out.
Pages, pages, pages.

39:05.761 --> 39:10.808
Genius, brilliant,
intellectual and otherwise pages.

39:10.975 --> 39:12.018
That's it.

39:13.102 --> 39:15.183
Beard: Suddenly I was working
a hundred hours a week.

39:15.312 --> 39:17.523
You know, I would
go home and go to bed

39:17.773 --> 39:19.150
and then wake up
the next morning

39:19.316 --> 39:21.819
and go to the office
and start writing again.

39:23.070 --> 39:24.447
Hendra: Henry, really,

39:24.613 --> 39:26.157
had become
the leader of the magazine.

39:26.323 --> 39:28.204
When Doug was still there,
it was a partnership,

39:28.367 --> 39:31.245
and when he left,
Henry was the only person

39:31.370 --> 39:33.914
who could actually, sort of,
be the final authority,

39:34.081 --> 39:36.709
and he had done that very,
I think, grudgingly.

39:37.251 --> 39:40.212
So when Doug sidled back
into the office,

39:40.379 --> 39:44.467
sort of saying, "Hi, I'm back,"
no one had much patience for Doug.

39:45.092 --> 39:48.220
He came back humbled,
deeply humbled.

39:48.387 --> 39:50.097
Deeply, sadly humbled.

39:50.264 --> 39:52.975
Tail between his legs.
He knew what he had done.

39:55.144 --> 39:57.271
Gross:
Doug brought the novel back,

39:57.438 --> 40:00.149
and Henry looks at it and goes,
"Jesus, this is awful."

40:00.316 --> 40:02.401
He... I... I read this thing,
it just made no sense.

40:02.568 --> 40:04.278
It was a complete nothing.

40:04.862 --> 40:06.989
And what he did was,
he opened up the window

40:07.156 --> 40:10.159
on Madison Avenue and just
scaled the whole thing out.

40:12.286 --> 40:14.006
Gross: There were people
not talking to him.

40:14.205 --> 40:16.886
And people were, like, doing this.
They didn't even want to see him.

40:17.625 --> 40:19.502
I was pissed at Doug,
and I said,

40:19.668 --> 40:21.921
"Doug, you know,
you fucking let me down.

40:23.172 --> 40:24.173
You let us all down."

40:33.724 --> 40:35.935
- Julius: This is Julius...
- Ethel: And Ethel...

40:36.102 --> 40:37.144
Both:
Rosenberg.

40:37.311 --> 40:40.356
Julius: Did you know that
the majority of dead people are Jews?

40:40.523 --> 40:45.152
Mm-hmm. 85% of all
dead people are Jewish.

40:45.444 --> 40:46.737
So remember,

40:46.904 --> 40:49.782
if you persecute Jews
when you're alive,

40:49.949 --> 40:53.244
boy, are you going to get it
when you're dead.

40:54.453 --> 40:57.331
Doug had just gotten back from
being AWOL for about a year,

40:57.498 --> 40:58.791
and I had just been hired.

40:58.958 --> 41:01.836
And Michael O'Donoghue,
in the early Lampoon,

41:02.002 --> 41:05.422
wrote a brief parody
of a high school year book.

41:05.589 --> 41:07.716
Matty Simmons had the idea
of turning this

41:07.883 --> 41:11.095
into a special edition
of doing a yearbook.

41:11.262 --> 41:14.431
Matty gave us the job because,
basically, we couldn't say no.

41:14.598 --> 41:17.977
Doug was still in the doghouse,
and I was a fresh hire.

41:18.144 --> 41:19.520
Simmons:
They weren't hot about the idea.

41:19.687 --> 41:22.565
But I wanted to do it,
and I pushed them.

41:22.731 --> 41:24.733
O'Rourke: We're sitting around,
bemoaning our fate.

41:24.900 --> 41:26.735
"This is such a stupid idea.

41:26.902 --> 41:28.571
How are we gonna
talk him out of this?"

41:29.155 --> 41:30.955
And we just started talking
about high school.

41:31.073 --> 41:33.284
And we started
talking about how, really,

41:33.450 --> 41:35.244
there are only a dozen people
in high school.

41:35.411 --> 41:36.971
Well, there's
the beautiful frigid girl,

41:36.996 --> 41:38.205
there's the stupid jock,

41:38.414 --> 41:40.416
there's the exchange student
from "Absurd-istan."

41:40.583 --> 41:43.085
You know, there's only a dozen,
18 people in high school.

41:44.211 --> 41:45.254
[music] (Chuck Berry "School
Days" plays) [music]

41:45.421 --> 41:46.422
Bingo.

41:48.424 --> 41:49.704
O'Rourke: This is how you do it.

41:49.717 --> 41:52.178
You cast these 18 characters,

41:52.344 --> 41:54.471
and you spin out a year
of their life,

41:54.638 --> 41:56.348
and you can get
a whole book out of this.

41:59.310 --> 42:00.895
Hirsch:
When I got to the Lampoon,

42:01.061 --> 42:03.564
Anne Beatts and Emily Prager
were the only two women writers.

42:03.731 --> 42:05.441
So I was desperate
to work on anything.

42:05.608 --> 42:08.194
And so I said to Doug Kenney,
"I volunteer.

42:08.360 --> 42:12.698
I will do anything
you want to help you."

42:13.073 --> 42:15.158
I walked with crutches,
I had polio as a kid.

42:15.326 --> 42:17.161
He said, "Oh, well, you know,
there's always a handicapped kid"

42:17.286 --> 42:18.287
"in every school."

42:18.454 --> 42:20.039
"Can we borrow
your crutches?"

42:20.664 --> 42:22.541
And I went,
"Well, not without me, you can't!"

42:22.708 --> 42:24.543
And so he said "All right,
well, will you be in it?"

42:24.710 --> 42:26.462
And I was Ursula Wattersky.

42:31.008 --> 42:33.594
I think P.J. was
the women's gym teacher.

42:33.761 --> 42:35.888
Brian McConnachie doing
the optometrist club,

42:36.055 --> 42:38.224
and they're all,
sort of, listing to the side.

42:38.390 --> 42:39.725
It was a wonderful experience.

42:39.892 --> 42:42.269
It was like producing
an independent movie.

42:43.771 --> 42:47.024
It was perfect for Doug
because he had simultaneously

42:47.191 --> 42:51.320
been just a regular high school guy
and Doug Kenney,

42:52.446 --> 42:54.406
super brain,
watching from on high.

42:55.199 --> 42:57.451
He wore his high school jacket
all the time, Doug.

42:57.618 --> 42:59.787
That was his natural costume.

42:59.954 --> 43:02.539
Doug used his own picture
as the dead student

43:02.665 --> 43:04.416
that the yearbook
was dedicated to.

43:05.084 --> 43:06.794
[music] (music continues) [music]

43:08.504 --> 43:11.382
It was a work of
true satirical brilliance.

43:11.548 --> 43:14.384
There were 50 storylines

43:14.551 --> 43:16.679
woven through it in all the different

43:16.845 --> 43:19.765
sections of it.
It was really a comic masterpiece.

43:21.141 --> 43:23.560
Gross: Doug was the personality
of National Lampoon.

43:23.727 --> 43:25.229
He understood...

43:26.981 --> 43:28.148
...people.

43:30.651 --> 43:32.152
(music stops)

43:33.988 --> 43:37.909
Simmons: Michael O'Donoghue
in the office was like a time bomb.

43:38.367 --> 43:40.160
You never knew
when it was going to go off.

43:40.327 --> 43:43.789
Michael O'Donoghue was... Seemed
to be the world's angriest guy.

43:43.956 --> 43:45.207
Simmons:
And he would scream and yell,

43:45.374 --> 43:47.293
and he would throw
telephone books.

43:47.459 --> 43:49.044
And the phone,
he'd rip the phone out

43:49.211 --> 43:51.630
and throw it across the office,
narrowly missing people.

43:52.006 --> 43:54.591
He was prone to,
when you're stuck,

43:54.758 --> 43:57.136
you turn around, you wanna
get angry at somebody.

43:57.303 --> 43:58.595
And you hit
the people closest to you.

43:58.762 --> 44:00.347
You start slapping them around.

44:00.973 --> 44:02.892
Hendra: Michael was like
a bundle of dynamite.

44:03.058 --> 44:05.811
For some reason, we hit it off
when I first came to the magazine.

44:06.228 --> 44:07.688
And we were friends for a while.

44:07.855 --> 44:10.107
As everybody was
with Michael, for a while.

44:12.067 --> 44:15.153
Beatts: Michael had gotten
into a giant feud with Tony

44:15.404 --> 44:18.949
over the fact that Tony had slept
with Michael's then-girlfriend, Amy.

44:19.116 --> 44:22.244
Michael marched into my office
and said, "You gotta fire him."

44:22.995 --> 44:25.914
And he told me what happened.
I said, "Michael, the one thing"

44:26.081 --> 44:28.792
"I never want to do is get
involved with the personal lives"

44:28.959 --> 44:30.461
"of the people who work here."

44:30.627 --> 44:34.381
Matty gave Michael
the National Lampoon Radio Hour

44:34.548 --> 44:36.467
as a compensatory thing.

44:36.633 --> 44:40.178
Like, okay, they have Lemmings,
you can have the Radio Hour.

44:40.596 --> 44:43.599
[music] (theme music plays) [music]

44:43.766 --> 44:45.851
- (knocking on door)
- Woman: Who is it?

44:46.018 --> 44:47.102
Man: Tom the Baker, here.

44:47.269 --> 44:49.313
Woman: Oh, Tom. Come on in.

44:49.480 --> 44:50.689
(door opens)

44:50.856 --> 44:52.316
You're not Tom the baker!

44:52.483 --> 44:53.692
Woman 2:
Watch out, he's got a knife.

44:53.859 --> 44:55.319
(woman 1 gasping)
Who are you?

44:55.486 --> 44:56.779
Man: I'm Bob the rapist.

44:56.945 --> 44:59.114
- Woman: Oh, Bob.
- Woman 2: Oh, Bob.

44:59.281 --> 45:00.949
Woman: Come on in,
have some coffee.

45:01.116 --> 45:02.368
Woman 2: Good to see you.

45:04.828 --> 45:07.039
In the beginning of the Radio Hour,
I guess it was envisioned

45:07.206 --> 45:08.832
that the editors
would be the writers.

45:08.999 --> 45:10.759
Michael had just sort of
written Lemmings off

45:10.876 --> 45:12.086
and everybody in it.

45:13.087 --> 45:15.087
One day, Chris Guest was
supposed to come in and do

45:15.130 --> 45:16.673
a Peter O'Toole imitation,

45:16.840 --> 45:18.509
and he called up
last minute to cancel.

45:19.009 --> 45:21.512
And I said,
"John can do Peter O'Toole."

45:21.678 --> 45:23.806
And that's how
everybody in Second City

45:23.972 --> 45:25.682
entered the Radio Hour.

45:25.849 --> 45:29.103
Gilda Radner: Hi, I'm your
host person, Gilda Radner,

45:29.269 --> 45:31.814
and I am going to read you
the people who contributed.

45:31.980 --> 45:34.316
John Belushi,
Brian Doyle-Murray,

45:34.483 --> 45:36.693
Bill Murray, Gilda Radner,
Harold "Rahmis",

45:36.860 --> 45:38.195
- Ed Subitzky.
- Harold Ramis: It's Ramis.

45:38.362 --> 45:40.280
- Gilda: What?
- Ramis: Ramis, not "Rahmis."

45:40.989 --> 45:42.908
Hirsch: These guys were
all Second City guys,

45:43.075 --> 45:47.371
