to a much larger audience.

58:27.505 --> 58:30.216
The Lampoon lost its exceptionalism.

58:30.425 --> 58:33.386
[music] (music plays) [music]

58:43.688 --> 58:45.690
[music] What would ya do [music]

58:45.857 --> 58:48.568
[music] If I sang out of tune [music]

58:48.735 --> 58:50.153
(applause)

58:50.320 --> 58:52.864
[music] Would you stand up
and walk out on me? [music]

58:53.031 --> 58:55.242
[music] Oh, baby,
I get high [music]

58:55.408 --> 58:58.119
[music] With a little help
from my friends [music]

58:58.286 --> 59:03.291
[music] Oh, yeah, whoa... [music]

59:03.458 --> 59:06.753
I've described the Lampoon as the
hippest place to be to write comedy.

59:06.920 --> 59:08.213
And it was,

59:08.379 --> 59:10.924
until the hippest place
to be to write comedy

59:11.090 --> 59:12.759
became Saturday Night Live.

59:14.093 --> 59:16.346
Chevy Chase came over
to the Lampoon offices,

59:16.512 --> 59:18.181
and, chuckling, he said,

59:18.348 --> 59:21.059
"Nobody gets laid writing for
the National Lampoon anymore."

59:30.568 --> 59:33.029
This friend of mine
tells me that Michael Gross

59:33.238 --> 59:34.864
is leaving the Lampoon,
the art director,

59:35.031 --> 59:36.366
and I should apply for the job.

59:36.658 --> 59:40.828
And, I walk into the conference room,
and Doug Kenney says to me,

59:40.995 --> 59:44.791
"Well, I have three questions:
Can you get us drugs?"

59:44.958 --> 59:46.918
"Can you get us nude models?"

59:47.085 --> 59:48.725
"And do you have some place
where we can go"

59:48.753 --> 59:50.463
"with the drugs
and the nude models?"

59:51.673 --> 59:53.758
And I thought very seriously

59:53.925 --> 59:58.554
and I said,
"Yes, yes, and yes."

59:59.597 --> 01:00:02.398
And Doug looked at me and he says,
"Well, I have no further questions."

01:00:02.558 --> 01:00:05.353
[music] (King Floyd's
"Groove Me" plays) [music]

01:00:07.814 --> 01:00:09.440
Abelson:
Peter had very little pretension

01:00:09.607 --> 01:00:11.901
in terms of art,
as did Michael Gross.

01:00:12.360 --> 01:00:15.196
Totally different kind of person
but he got it, you know,

01:00:15.363 --> 01:00:16.948
and that's the thing
that mattered.

01:00:17.115 --> 01:00:20.076
He was a great looking guy who
was not afraid to approach

01:00:20.243 --> 01:00:22.662
people of the opposite sex
and suggest

01:00:22.829 --> 01:00:24.669
that they might get
to know one another better,

01:00:24.831 --> 01:00:26.749
which was somewhat fascinating
to all of us.

01:00:27.417 --> 01:00:30.378
Every 30 days we were putting out
this 100-page magazine.

01:00:30.545 --> 01:00:33.506
Didn't matter how dirty,
or how vile, or how perverted,

01:00:33.673 --> 01:00:36.551
or how sexual, or how twisted
or violent it was.

01:00:36.718 --> 01:00:39.470
If it was funny,
and if Doug liked it, it was in.

01:00:48.730 --> 01:00:50.315
Simmons:
We knew all along that Doug

01:00:50.481 --> 01:00:51.983
and Henry Beard and Rob Hoffman

01:00:52.150 --> 01:00:54.652
would ask us to buy them out
after five years.

01:00:54.819 --> 01:01:00.616
However, the buyout said
that they would buy it out

01:01:00.783 --> 01:01:05.079
at 21 times earnings,
which was outrageous.

01:01:05.246 --> 01:01:07.790
They stood to make
a nice piece of change.

01:01:07.915 --> 01:01:10.543
I owed them seven and a half
million dollars.

01:01:11.294 --> 01:01:14.005
So we met with them
and we sat down and we talked.

01:01:14.964 --> 01:01:18.885
For whatever reason,
any reasonable alternative

01:01:19.052 --> 01:01:21.429
to the buyout was rejected.

01:01:22.764 --> 01:01:25.225
So when push came to shove,
we shoved.

01:01:25.391 --> 01:01:27.018
I don't think Matty
was prepared.

01:01:27.185 --> 01:01:30.230
I don't think Matty Simmons
really thought Doug and Henry

01:01:30.355 --> 01:01:31.356
would go through with it.

01:01:32.648 --> 01:01:33.649
And they did.

01:01:41.366 --> 01:01:45.703
Henry hinted a few times that,
you know,

01:01:45.870 --> 01:01:49.499
this could be good for you guys.
Meaning Sean, Tony and myself.

01:01:50.875 --> 01:01:53.711
O'Rourke: Other people apparently
felt that they were stake holders.

01:01:55.254 --> 01:01:58.132
And, um, you know, they weren't.

01:01:59.133 --> 01:02:01.886
They all thought Henry had
promised them a lot of money

01:02:02.053 --> 01:02:05.056
and he walked out of that office
the day the check was cashed.

01:02:05.223 --> 01:02:07.703
He stood up on a desk and said,
"I hated every minute of this."

01:02:07.850 --> 01:02:10.061
"Fuck you!" Then left.

01:02:11.187 --> 01:02:13.272
Kelly:
When Henry got up and told us

01:02:13.439 --> 01:02:15.149
that he was never going to talk
to any of us again,

01:02:15.316 --> 01:02:18.152
it was such a shattering
experience for all of us

01:02:18.319 --> 01:02:20.863
because he was the one
we were trying to please.

01:02:21.030 --> 01:02:22.615
I think the culture changed.

01:02:22.782 --> 01:02:26.119
And you know, people grew up.
It had a lifespan.

01:02:30.164 --> 01:02:31.457
Radio Announcer:
Never send care packages

01:02:31.624 --> 01:02:33.209
to the so-called starving families

01:02:33.376 --> 01:02:35.795
in Europe because they're not
starving at all.

01:02:35.962 --> 01:02:38.423
Can you afford to live in Europe?
No.

01:02:38.589 --> 01:02:40.091
You can't even afford
to visit Europe.

01:02:40.258 --> 01:02:42.760
And do you know what they do
with the care packages you send?

01:02:42.927 --> 01:02:44.448
They whack them
with their polo mallets

01:02:44.554 --> 01:02:46.114
and kick them into
their swimming pools.

01:02:46.889 --> 01:02:49.392
The first time I saw Doug
after the buyout,

01:02:49.559 --> 01:02:52.187
I said, "What are you going to
do with all of this bread?"

01:02:52.353 --> 01:02:53.604
"That's so great!"

01:02:53.771 --> 01:02:55.731
And Doug said,
"I'm going to Disneyland."

01:02:55.940 --> 01:02:59.068
[music] (rock music plays) [music]

01:02:59.235 --> 01:03:00.445
Doug was going to quit.

01:03:00.611 --> 01:03:02.331
He was wealthy now
and he was going to quit.

01:03:02.488 --> 01:03:04.532
And Matty was smart enough
to know that

01:03:04.699 --> 01:03:06.409
"Holy shit, if I lose Doug,

01:03:06.617 --> 01:03:08.738
I'm going to lose the heart
and soul of this company."

01:03:09.078 --> 01:03:10.599
And so he said,
"Well, don't quit Doug,

01:03:10.705 --> 01:03:13.291
we're going to make a movie."
And Doug went, "Really?"

01:03:13.458 --> 01:03:15.978
Once I told Doug we were making a
movie, we had to make a movie.

01:03:16.669 --> 01:03:20.047
Ivan then started coming up
with ideas with Harold Ramis.

01:03:20.298 --> 01:03:22.091
Reitman: I knew that the
High School Yearbook

01:03:22.258 --> 01:03:23.843
was the most popular thing

01:03:24.719 --> 01:03:26.429
that the National Lampoon
had ever put out.

01:03:26.596 --> 01:03:28.681
So I called up Doug Kenney
and said,

01:03:28.848 --> 01:03:31.976
"Hey, why don't you help Harold
write this high school movie?"

01:03:32.143 --> 01:03:33.784
They started writing
a screenplay that was

01:03:33.895 --> 01:03:35.813
Charlie Manson and his followers

01:03:35.980 --> 01:03:37.732
back when they were still
in high school.

01:03:37.899 --> 01:03:40.902
There was so much sex
and drinking and what have you

01:03:41.068 --> 01:03:45.072
involved with it that I said,
"We can't do this in high school.

01:03:45.531 --> 01:03:46.532
We'll get lynched."

01:03:46.699 --> 01:03:48.060
[music] (rock music plays) [music]

01:03:48.242 --> 01:03:51.370
So I spoke to Matty about shifting
away from high school to college

01:03:51.829 --> 01:03:55.041
and we were thinking of using
Chris Miller's stories.

01:03:55.208 --> 01:03:58.545
Simmons: Chris Miller was the
most popular short story writer

01:03:58.711 --> 01:03:59.962
in the history of the Lampoon.

01:04:00.129 --> 01:04:03.382
Reitman: He specialized in stories
based on his Dartmouth years.

01:04:03.674 --> 01:04:05.355
Chris Miller:
My stories were about college

01:04:05.593 --> 01:04:07.803
and getting loaded
and living a wild life

01:04:07.970 --> 01:04:09.680
and sex, drugs and rock'n'roll,

01:04:09.972 --> 01:04:11.682
or the absence of those things.

01:04:12.475 --> 01:04:13.893
Doug Kenney went crazy over it

01:04:14.143 --> 01:04:16.312
because they didn't do
shit like that at Harvard.

01:04:16.479 --> 01:04:18.040
Simmons:
Ramis, Kenney and Miller worked

01:04:18.147 --> 01:04:21.526
for a full year on what became
a 114 page treatment.

01:04:21.692 --> 01:04:23.528
The biggest treatment
anyone's ever seen.

01:04:23.694 --> 01:04:27.156
And so, that really
became Animal House.

01:04:30.576 --> 01:04:31.827
(rock music stops)

01:04:31.994 --> 01:04:35.706
After the buyout,
we bumped along until P.J.

01:04:35.873 --> 01:04:37.833
took the title of Editor-in-Chief.

01:04:38.000 --> 01:04:41.504
[music] (The Hombres
"Let It All Hang Out" plays) [music]

01:04:42.797 --> 01:04:46.217
I went to work as Matty's assistant
but I wound up as Editor-in-Chief

01:04:46.384 --> 01:04:49.470
because I had had some prior
publishing experience.

01:04:49.637 --> 01:04:52.640
I actually knew what on time
and under budget meant.

01:04:52.807 --> 01:04:55.727
The era of P.J. being
the Editor-in-Chief,

01:04:55.893 --> 01:04:58.688
it was less high-brow
and more approachable.

01:04:59.105 --> 01:05:00.856
Editorial meetings
were way different.

01:05:01.023 --> 01:05:04.026
Before he was editor,
editorial meetings were hanging out

01:05:04.193 --> 01:05:05.820
and trying to one-up each other

01:05:05.987 --> 01:05:08.072
and consisted of
this free-flow of ideas.

01:05:08.906 --> 01:05:12.118
When P.J. took over,
he was the chair of every meeting.

01:05:12.285 --> 01:05:13.645
He had an agenda on his legal pad.

01:05:13.703 --> 01:05:15.121
He would read us things
that he had written

01:05:15.288 --> 01:05:16.914
that he thought were
particularly funny.

01:05:17.832 --> 01:05:21.002
P.J. was one of those people
that really worked hard.

01:05:21.210 --> 01:05:23.504
It was not an endearing quality.

01:05:25.590 --> 01:05:30.803
It needed a grown-up,
but frankly, it stopped being fun.

01:05:34.682 --> 01:05:37.018
"How to talk your wife into oral sex:"

01:05:37.727 --> 01:05:42.649
"Beg, wheedle, plead,
moan, groan and whine."

01:05:42.815 --> 01:05:45.693
"The object being to have
her grab it in disgust"

01:05:45.860 --> 01:05:48.779
"and perform the dirty deed
to shut you up."

01:05:49.947 --> 01:05:51.032
By John Hughes.

01:05:51.198 --> 01:05:54.827
[music] (rock music plays) [music]

01:05:54.994 --> 01:05:57.079
Apatow: I was always an
enormous fan of John Hughes.

01:05:57.246 --> 01:06:00.458
He did all of this humor
about families and growing up

01:06:00.625 --> 01:06:03.419
and then really funny,
dirty stuff.

01:06:07.173 --> 01:06:08.453
When I was running the magazine,

01:06:08.549 --> 01:06:09.925
he was the best person
I had working for me.

01:06:10.217 --> 01:06:13.929
John could hue within,
sort of, one degree of reality

01:06:14.096 --> 01:06:15.181
and make it hilarious.

01:06:15.848 --> 01:06:18.288
Peter Kleinman: On the surface,
he was all-American, you know,

01:06:18.434 --> 01:06:20.436
almost like this nice family guy.

01:06:20.936 --> 01:06:23.522
And then you'd start
reading his stuff,

01:06:23.689 --> 01:06:27.068
and it was the most sick,
sexual, depraved,

01:06:27.234 --> 01:06:28.819
deviant stuff you've ever read.

01:06:31.822 --> 01:06:35.117
P.J. O'Rourke and John Hughes
and the kinds of articles they liked

01:06:35.284 --> 01:06:37.787
and wrote and edited
were politically different

01:06:37.953 --> 01:06:40.514
and culturally and socially different
than the stuff we had done.

01:06:40.581 --> 01:06:42.708
And the kinds of readers
changed also.

01:06:44.502 --> 01:06:46.462
Simmons:
I knew no one in Hollywood,

01:06:46.629 --> 01:06:49.173
but this is one of those things
that has to happen.

01:06:50.424 --> 01:06:54.512
You have to have luck
to go with talent.

01:06:57.390 --> 01:07:01.060
I got a phone call about a week
later from a guy who said,

01:07:01.227 --> 01:07:03.563
"Mr. Simmons,
I am the assistant to Ned Tanen"

01:07:03.729 --> 01:07:06.524
"at Universal Studios,
and I just want you to know"

01:07:06.691 --> 01:07:10.319
"that I'm a huge Lampoon freak
and if you ever want"

01:07:10.486 --> 01:07:12.113
"to do a movie, please call me."

01:07:12.363 --> 01:07:15.366
We met with Ned Tanen and he said,
"I hate this."

01:07:15.533 --> 01:07:19.203
"Everybody's a drunkard, a womanizer,
they're doing drugs."

01:07:19.370 --> 01:07:22.540
But he had two assistants:
Sean Daniel and Thom Mount,

01:07:22.707 --> 01:07:24.583
who had always thought
this project could work.

01:07:24.709 --> 01:07:25.793
And they were pushing it.

01:07:26.001 --> 01:07:27.253
As a National Lampoon fan,

01:07:27.420 --> 01:07:30.006
I just thought this is hilarious.

01:07:30.172 --> 01:07:33.008
Not everyone thought it was
as funny as I did.

01:07:33.175 --> 01:07:36.512
In fact, it was held
in total contempt.

01:07:37.304 --> 01:07:40.641
My deal was that if any part
of the National Lampoon show,

01:07:40.808 --> 01:07:44.103
which I produced, sort of,
led to what was going to be

01:07:44.270 --> 01:07:45.980
a National Lampoon movie

01:07:46.147 --> 01:07:48.607
then I was going to have
the opportunity to direct it.

01:07:48.774 --> 01:07:50.776
But the only film I had directed
up to that point

01:07:50.943 --> 01:07:53.654
was, uh, Cannibal Girls.

01:07:53.821 --> 01:07:55.462
Announcer: They love
every man they meet.

01:07:56.532 --> 01:07:59.118
First to death, then for dinner.

01:08:00.494 --> 01:08:03.372
Universal said, "Well, you can
produce it but you can't direct it."

01:08:03.706 --> 01:08:05.583
My girlfriend at the time
was working as

01:08:05.750 --> 01:08:08.043
a script supervisor
on Kentucky Fried Movie.

01:08:08.210 --> 01:08:10.337
She said to me
you have got to get to know

01:08:10.504 --> 01:08:12.065
the director of this movie,
John Landis.

01:08:13.549 --> 01:08:15.885
Sean approached me and said,
"Would you be interested

01:08:16.051 --> 01:08:18.595
in making a film at Universal?"

01:08:18.763 --> 01:08:21.474
And I was like, "Duh", and, uh,

01:08:21.640 --> 01:08:23.559
he gave me
the script to Animal House.

01:08:23.725 --> 01:08:25.406
Ned Tanen took me
into his office and said,

01:08:25.435 --> 01:08:27.979
"Look, a lot of people
around here hate this"

01:08:28.147 --> 01:08:29.398
"and don't think
we should be doing it."

01:08:29.564 --> 01:08:30.816
"But if you believe in it,"

01:08:30.983 --> 01:08:32.984
"go away and bring us back
a movie."

01:08:37.238 --> 01:08:40.075
You can't spend your whole life
worrying about your mistakes.

01:08:40.242 --> 01:08:42.620
You fucked up!
You trusted us!

01:08:44.997 --> 01:08:46.415
I had never done a comedy,

01:08:46.582 --> 01:08:49.376
and I just was so over
where my career was.

01:08:49.542 --> 01:08:51.545
I was like,
"I have to be in this movie."

01:08:51.712 --> 01:08:53.255
(loud crack)

01:08:53.339 --> 01:08:54.799
Thank you, sir.
May I have another?

01:08:56.675 --> 01:08:58.036
Bacon:
I auditioned for John Landis

01:08:58.176 --> 01:09:00.554
and he said,
"Yeah, this guy is smarmy,

01:09:00.720 --> 01:09:03.224
he's a smarmy guy.
Can ya do that?"

01:09:03.599 --> 01:09:05.350
I had no idea
what the word smarmy meant,

01:09:05.518 --> 01:09:10.104
so I just, kind of, made this face
and he was like, "That's great!"

01:09:11.064 --> 01:09:13.859
My kid can't see, is it all right
if he stands in front of you?

01:09:14.026 --> 01:09:15.027
No!

01:09:16.904 --> 01:09:18.738
Landis: I really wanted
the writers on set.

01:09:18.906 --> 01:09:21.158
Universal of course,
this is a low-budget picture,

01:09:21.325 --> 01:09:22.827
told me to go fuck myself, so...

01:09:23.368 --> 01:09:26.872
What I did, was I said,
"Look, get yourself to Eugene

01:09:27.038 --> 01:09:29.375
and I will hire you
every day as actors."

01:09:29.707 --> 01:09:31.794
Chris and Doug
being there was important.

01:09:32.086 --> 01:09:35.923
And Doug Kenney,
really important because,

01:09:36.131 --> 01:09:38.008
you know, we made up a lot
of stuff shooting.

01:09:38.175 --> 01:09:40.426
What the hell
we supposed to do, you moron?

01:09:40.594 --> 01:09:42.470
Doug was always the smartest guy
in the room,

01:09:42.595 --> 01:09:44.765
you know, and the richest guy.
(chuckling)

01:09:45.140 --> 01:09:46.725
And the one with the drugs.

01:09:47.017 --> 01:09:50.062
So, it was a real special time
because it was a chance

01:09:50.229 --> 01:09:52.689
to meet all these people
that I had always revered.

01:09:52.857 --> 01:09:55.943
You know, the Lampoon
and that Doug had founded it

01:09:56.110 --> 01:09:59.363
and was as smart in person
and funny in person

01:09:59.530 --> 01:10:01.782
as the magazine was.

01:10:01.949 --> 01:10:03.951
Landis: I know that for Doug,
he was in heaven.

01:10:04.326 --> 01:10:05.536
He had the time of his life.

01:10:07.997 --> 01:10:11.250
But Ned Tanen was very upset
about it and very concerned

01:10:11.417 --> 01:10:13.669
and really we were in trouble
for a while.

01:10:13.919 --> 01:10:15.462
When he saw the movie he just...

01:10:15.921 --> 01:10:19.341
He didn't like it and, uh,
didn't find any of it funny.

01:10:22.094 --> 01:10:23.774
Sean Daniel:
Came time to preview the movie

01:10:23.929 --> 01:10:26.807
in front of
an actual paying audience,

01:10:27.266 --> 01:10:29.268
the president
of the corporation came,

01:10:29.435 --> 01:10:32.313
who had been one of
the non-believers.

01:10:33.772 --> 01:10:36.358
And all of
the executives were there.

01:10:36.525 --> 01:10:39.945
The time has come for someone
to put his foot down,

01:10:40.988 --> 01:10:43.073
and that foot is me.

01:10:43.574 --> 01:10:45.409
It was, you know,
you're sitting there very nervous,

01:10:45.576 --> 01:10:46.816
"How will they like the movie?"

01:10:47.661 --> 01:10:49.830
(screaming)

01:10:50.039 --> 01:10:51.123
They went nuts.

01:10:51.373 --> 01:10:53.083
(cheering)

01:10:54.752 --> 01:10:57.546
Suddenly the studio went,
"Oh, my God, this really worked."

01:10:57.838 --> 01:10:59.423
Landis:
And from that moment on,

01:10:59.590 --> 01:11:03.093
we went from being criminals...
Suspects to heroes.

01:11:07.681 --> 01:11:11.143
I remember seeing it with my mom.
It was the first time I saw

01:11:11.310 --> 01:11:13.520
women's breasts
in front of my mother.

01:11:13.938 --> 01:11:15.815
I literally can remember how
many people were in the theater

01:11:15.981 --> 01:11:19.026
and what it looked like
and my red shamed face.

01:11:19.401 --> 01:11:22.905
And you have to remember that
Animal House created a genre.

01:11:23.072 --> 01:11:25.449
[music] (Bobby Lewis
"Tossin' and Turnin'" plays) [music]

01:11:28.118 --> 01:11:29.411
So we figured,
"Wow, this is awesome."

01:11:29.578 --> 01:11:31.038
Everybody's going to love
the magazine now

01:11:31.205 --> 01:11:33.040
and see that we're more
mainstream because of this movie

01:11:33.207 --> 01:11:34.792
which was a huge success.

